<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> My Love Affair With a Guy Named Nertea<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.67)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=7058'>Jonathan "Carny" brown</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=7058&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> December 5, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Ah! We’ve all experienced it, your opponent just gave you like three hundred and fifty seven twilight by playing 9 companions, seventy four weapons and using Uncommon Gimli to put an entire 17 card hand under their draw deck. Yes, I know he’s been errataed, loosen up! So, your opponent is moving, and you only have 8 cards in you hand. That means that, if you were lucky and had 8 minions in your hand(which we both know is impossible, if your luck is anything like mine) you still fall one short of touching Frodo, much less killing him AND Sam. Whatever do you do? Well, hopefully you had the forsight to play with Ulaire Nertea, the best minion in the game, hands down, in the current environment,<br />
<br />
This article is designed to give all the reasons, theories and weird ideas as to why Ulaire Nertea, Messenger of Dol Guldur, belongs in every single deck, no matter what the deck is trying to do. In fact, I am going to try and convince you that no less than TWO copies should be required, by law, to be in every tournament viable Shadow Side. Whether I am successful or not, hopefully this article will be funny, entertaining, or at least take up some time at work, in the cubicle, or behind the counter, or whatever. Heck, maybe you’ll even read it because you want to, I dunno, maybe somebody is that smart J<br />
<br />
Well, where to begin? First of all, we’ll go with the stats of this lovely card!<br />
<br />
Minions: Nazgul<br />
Twilight Cost: 4<br />
Strength: 9<br />
Vitality: 2<br />
Home Site: 3<br />
Gametext: When you play Ulaire Nertea, you may play a minion from your discard pile for each companion over 4.<br />
<br />
WOW! Wasn’t that amazing? I can type!<br />
<br />
Anyways, right off the bat, you can see that Nertea(Nerty from here on out) has pretty standard stats for minions from TTT, but he falls a little behind compared to some of the Uruks from FOTR, since he costs 4 and they cost 3. Anyways, he stops roaming early, which means that at the very least, he’ll help you put a little pressure on your opponent in the early game. But, we all know that that’s not his main purpose. Lets go back to the scenario in the first paragraph. Lets say that you drew up 5 minions to play against your opponent’s 9 companions. Assuming that your opponent is moving to site 9, your would imagine that you were pretty darn screwed, and you would be right, unless one of those 5 minions is Ulaire Nertea. Now, lets say you are playing Uruks, which is a safe assumption these days, and the 4 other minions are 2 Uruk Warriors, an Uruk Regular and an Uruk Ravager. Well, the Uruk Ravager doesn’t look so good right now, does he, since Saruman is no where to be found, but hey look! Nerty can go get Saruman, along with 3 other fellas, to come and whoop some Fellowship Behind! So, start off by playing Nerty, then grab 4 other guys, starting with Saruman. Then, grab 3 more Ravagers, for 2 Twilight each, and then drop the other Ravager. You now have 4 9 Strength Fierce Minions, Saruman and a 9 Strength Nazgul, all from 2 cards in your hand. Amazing. Follow up with the 3 other Uruks from your hand and watch your opponent cry. Now, imagine you had unlimited Twilight, so now you pull Saruman, 2 Lieutenants and a Captain, using the Captain to pull ANOTHER Lietenant. Ugh, now we begin to see why Uruks are so so good, and even more so the versatility afforded by playing with Nerty.<br />
<br />
Need to get rid of Filbert? Use Nerty to grab a Tower Assassin, or a Dunlanding Looter(I think he’s the one that eats allies….all those unwashed Wild Men look the same to me)<br />
Opponent looking bad on burdens? Grab an Enquear, who goes wonderfully with Nerty, or a Berserker!<br />
I think that most of you can already see why Nerty is so freakin’ good, so I’ll stop with the talkin’ about that.<br />
<br />
Sooooo, Nerty is so good, why doesn’t everyone play him? THAT’S WHAT I’M SAYIN’! Ahem, I mean, of course there are reasons not to play him. If most people in your area are playin’ small tight fellowships, then of course, Nerty becomes a LOT less efficient. Fortunately for ol’ Nerty, the trend is currently leaning toward dumping companions out and running for the woods. <br />
The main drawback to playin’ with Nerty is due to ONE card that gets played in almost all tourney decks. O Elbereth! Gilthoniel! <br />
For those of you without ready access to this card…or those too lazy to read it, heres the text:<br />
<br />
Condition<br />
Twilight: 1<br />
Gametext: Plays on the Ringbearer.<br />
Skirmish: Discard this condition to cancel a skirmish involving the Ringbearer and a Nazgul OR to take off the One Ring.<br />
+1 Strength<br />
<br />
As you can see, this is a wonderful card, purely for the low cost permanent Strength bonus. The problem comes when you get out TONS of minions against their fellowship, including enough to triple team Frodo. If your opponent has out OEG, all they have to do is make sure that Frodo is fighting at least one Nazgul(cough,Nerty,cough) and then you can have as much strength on Frodo as you want, and he’s not going ANYWHERE. <br />
For this reason, in any deck that plays Nerty, much less any deck PERIOD, I recommend some reliable form of Free Peoples condition removal, such as Saruman’s Power, the Pale Blade, Discovered, Wild Man Raid(AWESOME card) or, ummmm, I can’t think of any more, but I am SURE there are more. <br />
<br />
Another aspect of ol’ Nerty that I want to stress is how strong he is is Draft and Sealed deck. One of the best things about the new Draft Packs is that almost all of them include one copy of, you guessed it, Ulaire Nertea(yep, Nerty himself) to control the large numbers on companions included in those same Draft Packs. If you have the pleasure of playing in a Draft, or even a Sealed Deck, thank God when you see Nertea on your side of the table, and always consider how you would handle your opponent playing him against you, which brings me to the next section of my article!<br />
So Jonathan you say, now that you have shown me the power, and how to work around the weaknesses of, Ulaire Nertea, how do I stop him from ruining my next game? Well my friend, to you I say, play only 4 companions! Oh, that’s not good enough for you, eh? Well, while that is the only TRULY safe way to avoid being Nertead, there are other ways to prepare for him. The most important one is to play with OEG, and to know how to use it to save your butt. Aside from that, watch the minions that your opponent is playing. If they are playing lots of unique minions and you see that they might be relying on playing the same one after you kill it, leave the unique ones alive and off the non uniques. Secondly, if you have Nertea played on you, and you are still planning on double moving(which means either your opponent mis-played Nerty, or you had some surprises), don’t kill him off. If your opponent is smart enough to play one Nerty, they probably were smart enough to stock two. By not killing the first one, not only will your opponent NOT be able to play the other Nerty card in their hand, but they won’t be able to use his game text again. HUGE.<br />
<br />
Well, though I am surprised by how much I was able to write simply about Ulaire Nertea, I have finally run out of things to say about him. For those of you who either forgot, or were just too lazy to read the whole thing, heres the run-down of Nerty’s uses:<br />
<br />
1)	Hand extension…more minions per card than any other in the game.<br />
2)	Versatility…grab the minions you need to get the job done<br />
3)	He’s a good minion MINUS his gametext!<br />
4)	 Beware O Elbereth! Gilthoniel!<br />
5)	Draft him if you can<br />
6)	Don’t kill him if you’re gonna double move!<br />
<br />
Well, hopefully you all enjoyed what I’ve had to say, if not, sorry! Maybe I’ll write an article about Lightfootedness, the other card that belongs in every deck! Heh Heh, half of you just went flipping through your cards, trying to figure out what you missed about that card, and the other half you are vowing to never read another one of my articles! For those of you feeling brave, or REALLY bored, check my other articles, especially Hamtaro Parallels in Lord of the Rings, it’s quite funny. <br />
<br />
That’s it for now, catch you on the flipside…or something, and beware Frank the Evil Time-Traveling Bunny!<br />
<br />
The Carny<br />
